<p>Texas is the second-largest state economy in the United States, driven by oil and gas production, a rapidly expanding technology sector centered on Austin, major agricultural output, and one of the most active logistics and manufacturing corridors in North America. Dallas-Fort Worth, Houston, Austin, and San Antonio each rank among the largest metropolitan economies in the country. Texas's workforce spans roughnecks on West Texas oil rigs, software engineers in Austin's Silicon Hills, construction workers across the state's booming housing market, and an enormous gig economy workforce in its major cities.</p>

<p>One significant advantage for Texas workers: the state has no state income tax. That means your pay stub deductions are limited to federal income tax, Social Security, Medicare, and any voluntary or employer-mandated deductions. This generator calculates all applicable taxes and produces a professional PDF pay stub instantly.</p>

<h2>Texas Income Tax Rates</h2>

<p>Texas has a 0% state income tax rate. The Texas Constitution prohibits a personal income tax, and any attempt to enact one would require a constitutional amendment approved by voters. This makes Texas one of nine states with no state income tax, alongside Florida, Nevada, Washington, Wyoming, South Dakota, Alaska, New Hampshire, and Tennessee.</p>

<p>The absence of state income tax does not mean Texas workers pay no state taxes -- Texas funds its government largely through sales tax (6.25% state rate, up to 8.25% with local additions) and property taxes, which are among the highest in the nation. But none of these appear as deductions on your pay stub.</p>

<p>On a Texas pay stub, you will see only federal deductions:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Federal income tax:</strong> Calculated using the IRS's graduated bracket system (10% to 37% depending on income level)</li>
  <li><strong>Social Security tax:</strong> 6.2% of gross wages up to the $168,600 wage base (2024)</li>
  <li><strong>Medicare tax:</strong> 1.45% of all gross wages, with an additional 0.9% on wages above $200,000 annually</li>
</ul>

<p>Workers in Texas take home more per paycheck than comparable workers in high-tax states. A Texas software engineer earning $120,000 annually avoids roughly $6,000 to $8,000 in state income tax compared to a California counterpart at similar income levels, though the comparison is complex given Texas's higher property taxes and cost factors.</p>

<h2>Does Texas Require Pay Stubs?</h2>

<p>Texas does not have a state law mandating that employers provide pay stubs to employees. Under Texas law, employers are not required to provide written earnings statements, though they must comply with federal record-keeping requirements under the Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA).</p>

<p>However, the vast majority of Texas employers do provide pay stubs voluntarily, both as a practical matter for payroll reconciliation and because employees reasonably expect them. Large Texas employers -- ExxonMobil, AT&T, American Airlines, Texas Instruments -- all provide detailed electronic pay stubs through payroll portals.</p>

<p>For workers who do not receive formal pay stubs -- construction subcontractors, oil field day-rate workers, cash-paid domestic workers, gig drivers -- this generator fills that gap by creating documentation that meets the format landlords and lenders expect. No Texas law requires employers to provide pay stubs, but federal FLSA §211(c) requires employers to maintain payroll records for a minimum of three years.</p>

<h2>Pay Stub Requirements in Texas</h2>

<p>Because Texas has no state pay stub mandate, the requirements are set by federal law and employer policy. Federal FLSA record-keeping rules require employers to track and retain:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Employee's full name and identifying number</li>
  <li>Home address including zip code</li>
  <li>Date of birth if under 19</li>
  <li>Sex and occupation</li>
  <li>Time and day of week when the workweek begins</li>
  <li>Regular hourly rate of pay</li>
  <li>Total daily or weekly straight-time earnings</li>
  <li>Total overtime earnings for the workweek</li>
  <li>All additions to or deductions from wages</li>
  <li>Total wages paid each pay period</li>
  <li>Date of payment and pay period covered</li>
</ul>

<p>Even without a state mandate to give this information to employees, best practice -- and what most landlords and lenders expect -- is a pay stub that includes: employer name and address, employee name, pay period dates, gross wages, all deductions itemized, and net pay.</p>

<h2>Pay Frequency Laws in Texas</h2>

<p>Texas Labor Code Section 61.011 requires that employers pay wages at least twice a month (semi-monthly) for most employees. However, there are specific provisions:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Most employees:</strong> Must be paid at least semi-monthly (24 pay periods per year)</li>
  <li><strong>Exempt executive, administrative, or professional employees:</strong> May be paid monthly</li>
  <li><strong>Agricultural employees:</strong> May be paid monthly</li>
  <li><strong>Commissioned salespeople:</strong> May be paid monthly</li>
</ul>

<p>Texas does not have specific "wage theft prevention" legislation comparable to New York's or California's, but employees who are not paid in full on schedule can file wage claims with the Texas Workforce Commission (TWC). The TWC investigates wage complaints and can order back wages plus a penalty equal to the unpaid wages.</p>

