<p><strong>Oil and gas workers:</strong> The Permian Basin and Eagle Ford shale plays employ tens of thousands of drilling, completion, and production workers, many of whom work on per-diem or day-rate contracts rather than traditional employment. Day-rate workers often have no payroll department generating stubs. When a Midland roughneck wants to finance a truck or apply for a mortgage, they need income documentation in a format banks can work with. This generator creates that documentation based on actual earned income.</p>

<p><strong>Construction workers:</strong> Texas's housing boom has created massive demand for construction labor across DFW, Austin, San Antonio, and Houston. Construction subcontractors -- electricians, plumbers, framers, roofers -- frequently work as sole proprietors or through small LLCs without formal payroll systems. Generated stubs based on actual job earnings serve as essential income documentation.</p>

<p><strong>Austin tech workers:</strong> Austin has attracted major employers including Tesla, Oracle, Dell, and a massive startup ecosystem. Technology workers who contract independently or consult between positions need pay stub documentation for housing in one of the country's most competitive rental markets.</p>

<p><strong>Gig workers in major Texas cities:</strong> Houston, Dallas, and Austin all have large gig economies. DoorDash, Uber Eats, Lyft, and Amazon Flex do not issue pay stubs. Workers relying on these platforms as their primary income source need generated stubs for apartment applications. See our <a href="/pay-stub-for-apartment">pay stub for apartment applications</a> guide for specifics on what Texas property managers typically require.</p>


