<h2>Frequently Asked Questions for Texas Workers</h2>

<h3>Since Texas has no income tax, does my pay stub look different from other states?</h3>
<p>Yes. Your Texas pay stub will show $0.00 for state income tax withholding. The deductions section will only show federal income tax, Social Security (6.2%), and Medicare (1.45%). This means your net pay -- what you actually take home -- is higher than it would be at the same gross pay in a state with income tax. A Texas worker earning $5,000 per month gross takes home roughly $400 to $500 more per month than a comparable worker in California, depending on income level and deductions.</p>

<h3>I work in the oilfield and get paid a day rate. How do I calculate my gross pay?</h3>
<p>Multiply your daily rate by the number of days worked during the pay period. For example, if you earn $350 per day and worked 14 days in a two-week period, your gross pay is $4,900. Enter this as your gross pay in the salary field and select your pay frequency. If you work inconsistent schedules, generate a separate stub for each pay period with that period's actual earnings. For ongoing documentation, see the <a href="/self-employed-pay-stub-generator">self-employed pay stub generator</a>, which has more detail on how to document variable income.</p>

<h3>Does Texas have any payroll taxes that affect my take-home pay?</h3>
<p>Texas has no employee-side payroll taxes beyond federal FICA. Employers pay Texas unemployment insurance (SUTA) which does not appear on employee pay stubs. There is no state disability insurance, no state-level SDI, and no paid family leave deductions. Your Texas pay stub deductions are purely federal.</p>

<h3>I'm a DoorDash driver in Texas. What employer name should I use on my pay stub?</h3>
<p>Use "DoorDash, Inc." as the employer and your own name as the employee. Include your gross earnings from the DoorDash earnings report for the pay period, and note "Independent Contractor" rather than a traditional job title. For generating multiple stubs covering different pay periods, make sure each stub reflects the actual earnings from that specific period -- do not average income across periods. Consistency with your bank deposit records matters when a property manager reviews the documentation. Our <a href="/pay-stub-template">pay stub template guide</a> covers the field layout in detail.</p>

<h3>Can I use a Texas pay stub generator for mortgage pre-qualification?</h3>
<p>Mortgage lenders in Texas require specific income documentation. For W-2 employees, pay stubs work well as part of the documentation package. For self-employed borrowers, lenders typically want two years of tax returns plus a year-to-date profit and loss statement in addition to -- not instead of -- pay stub documentation. The <a href="/pay-stub-for-mortgage">pay stub for mortgage</a> page details exactly what Texas mortgage underwriters require by loan type (conventional, FHA, VA). Texas has a significant VA loan market given the large military presence at Fort Hood, Fort Sam Houston, and other installations, and VA lenders have specific income documentation standards.</p>

